{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487356"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:07:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:07:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"329"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582575"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:47:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:47:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"329"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/329"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.07,0.19,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"329"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103533"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/329"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"329"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85949"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1453"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12441"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31906"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42061"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43001"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103533"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review of his hypertension and diabetes management. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history and drinks about two glasses of wine a day. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus diagnosed 10 years ago, hyperlipidaemia, and stage 2 chronic kidney disease. His current medications are metformin and atorvastatin. Lisinopril was started three months ago but discontinued due to persistent dry cough.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His blood pressure is 160/90 mmHg, and pulse rate 90/min. The rest of the examination is unremarkable. His BMI is 29 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Recent investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHbA1c: 7.8% (62 mmol/mol)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 58 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (60-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine albumin-to-creatinine ratio: 45 mg/g (0-30).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Valsartan","Metoprolol","Amlodipine","Indapamide","Furosemide"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with poorly controlled hypertension, diabetes, and evidence of early diabetic nephropathy (microalbuminuria). The most appropriate next step in management is to commence \u003Cstrong\u003Evalsartan\u003C/strong\u003E. This addresses several key aspects of the patient\u0027s condition:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EValsartan\u003C/strong\u003E, an angiotensin receptor blocker (ARB), is an excellent choice for this patient. ARBs are preferred in patients with diabetes and microalbuminuria, especially when ACE inhibitors are not tolerated due to cough, as in this case. ARBs provide renoprotection by reducing intraglomerular pressure and proteinuria, which is crucial given the patient\u0027s chronic kidney disease and microalbuminuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E, a beta-blocker, is less ideal. Beta-blockers are not first-line for hypertension but can be used if the patient also has stable angina and after a myocardial infarction. Cardio-specific beta-blockers are also used in heart failure with reduced ejection fraction and include bisoprolol, carvedilol, nebivolol, and metoprolol succinate (as opposed to metoprolol tartrate).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E, a calcium channel blocker, could be a reasonable choice, but it does not offer the same renoprotective benefits as an ARB. In patients with diabetes and chronic kidney disease, combination therapy is often necessary to achieve blood pressure targets, which are lower (130/80 mmHg) than for the general population. Amlodipine could be considered as an add-on therapy if valsartan alone is insufficient to control blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndapamide\u003C/strong\u003E, a thiazide-like diuretic, can be useful in hypertension management, but it does not offer the same renoprotective benefits as an ARB. It could be considered as an add-on therapy if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E, a loop diuretic, is not appropriate as first-line therapy in this case. Loop diuretics are generally reserved for more advanced stages of chronic kidney disease or heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the current Australian guidelines for hypertension management (2016), blood pressure targets should be individualised through shared decision-making between patient and clinician, taking into account the potential benefits and harms of treatment, and reviewed regularly. In general, a target blood pressure of \u0026lt;140/90 mmHg is recommended for patients with uncomplicated hypertension. However, in patients such as this one, who are at high of cardiovascular risk (given his diabetes with microalbuminuria) more intensive systolic blood pressure targets (\u0026lt;120 mmHg) may be appropriate. However, such targets require careful monitoring for treatment-related adverse effects, including hypotension, syncope, electrolyte disturbances, and acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, valsartan offers the best balance of blood pressure control and renoprotection for this patient with diabetes, hypertension, and early diabetic nephropathy. It is important to note that while valsartan is the best initial choice, combination therapy may be necessary to achieve target blood pressure. The patient should be closely monitored, and additional agents (such as amlodipine) may need to be added if blood pressure remains uncontrolled on valsartan alone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Angiotensin receptor blockers (ARBs) are preferred over ACE inhibitors in patients with diabetes and microalbuminuria who cannot tolerate ACE inhibitors due to cough."],"references":["Vijan S. Diabetes: treating hypertension. BMJ Clin Evid [Internet]. 2012;2012:03:608\u201336 [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3275142/","National Heart Foundation of Australia. Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults \u2013 2016 [Internet]. Melbourne: National Heart Foundation of Australia; 2016 [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://assets.contentstack.io/v3/assets/blt8a393bb3b76c0ede/bltbf3d36e10b48f01f/65b0963ea933e532ae0286de/01_Hypertension-guideline-2016_WEB.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85949"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"329"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85949"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-23T14:12:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-23T14:12:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"329"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103533"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,